<subSubSection lastPageId="69" lastPageNumber="465" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="68.[813,1452,1337,1553]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,923,1337,1361]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doflein" authorityYear="1904" box="[932,1034,1337,1361]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1034,1337,1361]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Hexaplax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by the large hammershaped cornea, and long, slender P2–P4, and has long believed to be monotypic. Examination of recent collections from 
<collectingCountry box="[872,953,1433,1457]" name="Taiwan" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, the 
<collectingCountry box="[1005,1125,1433,1457]" name="Philippines" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1179,1387,1433,1457]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
show that specimens from the Pacific belong to two new species. It is a deep-water genus, with all three species collected from 
<quantity box="[873,1024,1529,1553]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" unit="m" value="450.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="400.0">
400 to 
<specimenCount box="[951,1024,1529,1553]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" type="generic">500 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="68.[813,1452,1593,2097]" lastBlockId="69.[136,775,188,245]" lastPageId="69" lastPageNumber="465" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">
The record of “ 
<taxonomicName box="[979,1120,1593,1617]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[979,1081,1593,1617]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Hexaplax</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
” by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun MJ" box="[1173,1390,1593,1617]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" pagination="301 - 367" refId="ref46212" refString="Rathbun MJ (1910) Brachyura. V. In: The Danish Expedition to Siam 1899 - 1900. Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskabs Skrifter, Kjobenhavn, (7) 5 (4): 301 - 367, pls. 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="1910">Rathbun (1910: 349</bibRefCitation>
, textfig. 37) from the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[1077,1172,1625,1649]" name="Thailand" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Thailand</collectingCountry>
is problematic. Her figure of the carapace (
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun MJ" box="[994,1159,1657,1681]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" pagination="301 - 367" refId="ref46212" refString="Rathbun MJ (1910) Brachyura. V. In: The Danish Expedition to Siam 1899 - 1900. Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskabs Skrifter, Kjobenhavn, (7) 5 (4): 301 - 367, pls. 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="1910">Rathbun, 1910</bibRefCitation>
: text-fig. 37a) superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doflein" authorityYear="1904" box="[935,1158,1689,1713]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalops">
<emphasis box="[935,1158,1689,1713]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Hexaplax megalops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(or one of the other two species) and Rathbun commented that it had reniform eyes. However, it was a very small male only 
<quantity box="[1335,1421,1753,1777]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
in carapace width and in poor condition. Most surprisingly, it was obtained in only six fathoms (ca. 
<quantity box="[1237,1294,1817,1841]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" unit="m" value="11.0">11 m</quantity>
) of water that is much shallower than what is known for members of this genus which are almost always from the deep sea, in excess of 
<specimenCount box="[842,917,1913,1937]" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" type="generic">
<quantity box="[842,914,1913,1937]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
The third maxilliped she figured (
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun MJ" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" pagination="301 - 367" refId="ref46212" refString="Rathbun MJ (1910) Brachyura. V. In: The Danish Expedition to Siam 1899 - 1900. Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskabs Skrifter, Kjobenhavn, (7) 5 (4): 301 - 367, pls. 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="1910">Rathbun, 1910: 349</bibRefCitation>
, text-fig. 37b), however, suggests that her specimen is not a 
<taxonomicName box="[875,1065,1977,2001]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[875,977,1977,2001]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Hexaplax</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, being elongated with a rectangular ischium and the dactylus is shorter than the propodus. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doflein" authorityYear="1904" box="[813,918,2041,2065]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="68" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,918,2041,2065]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Hexaplax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ischium is much shorter and broader, and the dactylus is much longer than the propodus (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1448,2073,2097]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="77.[138,173,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[144,1470,858,2018]" captionTargetId="figure-7@77.[83,1491,825,2046]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Fig. 62. Hexaplax megalops Doflein, 1904. A–D, male (18.7 × 12.1 mm) (MNHN-IU-2011-2251); E, female (17.7 × 12.2 mm) (MNHN- IU-2011-2251). A, left third maxilliped; B, male abdomen and telson; C, D, G1; E, female abdomen and telson. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354083/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="464">Figs. 62A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[136,185,188,212]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="80.[113,148,2063,2085]" captionTargetBox="[119,1442,657,2023]" captionTargetId="figure-11@80.[80,1475,618,2039]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="Fig. 64. Hexaplax aurantium, new species. A–D, holotype male (15.3 × 10.8 mm) (MNHN-IU-2011-2158); E, paratype female (13.2 × 9.5 mm). A, left third maxilliped; B, male abdomen and telson; C, D, G1; E, female abdomen and telson. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354087/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="465">64A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[198,248,188,212]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="82.[113,148,2064,2086]" captionTargetBox="[117,1442,1043,2039]" captionTargetId="figure-11@82.[82,1523,1007,2045]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="Fig. 66. Hexaplax saudade, new species. A–D, holotype male (16.4 × 12.1 mm) (NMCR); E, paratype female (13.1 × 9.7 mm). A, left third maxilliped; B, male abdomen and telson; C, D, G1; E, female abdomen and telson. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354091/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="465">66A</figureCitation>
). This specimen will need to be re-examined to ascertain what genus it belongs to.
</paragraph>
